{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"275e4d10-6212-4a1c-98cb-4bb567044d3d","content":"Your project isn't at that path in this workspace, but here's how to configure it.\n\nCreate or edit `.vscode/mcp.json` in your workspace root:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n      \"command\": \"dotnet\",\n      \"args\": [\"run\", \"--project\", \"src/MyMcpServer/MyMcpServer.csproj\"]\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- **`type: \"stdio\"`** — Copilot communicates with your server over stdin/stdout.\n- **`command` / `args`** — Uses `dotnet run` to build and launch your project.\n- Your server must use **stdio transport** (not HTTP). If you're using the `ModelContextProtocol` NuGet package, configure it with `.WithStdioServerTransport()`.\n\nAfter saving, open the Copilot Chat panel in agent mode (`@`), and your server's tools will be available. You can verify by clicking the 🔧 icon in the chat input.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"cb20912e-3117-47e6-9dcf-1f736b621797","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The project doesn't exist yet, but that's fine — the user is asking how to configure `mcp.json`, not asking me to build the project. I can provide guidance on configuring MCP for VS Code agent mode with a C# MCP server using stdio transport.","outputTokens":336,"requestId":"3861:28CF3A:6D4CCEE:75B397A:6A03CFAD"},"id":"b4b945d2-c81c-4fa9-a08d-868b91d83416","timestamp":"2026-05-13T01:11:18.589Z","parentId":"c5db428f-4e54-4b5a-906e-22cf30808812"}
